Technically you can have full siblings with no common DNA ancestry. Say mom is half Scots, half Chinese. And dad is also 50% Scots and 50% Chinese.
Daughter is born. The 50% she happens to get from mom is the moms Scots DNA. The 50% she happens to get from dad is the dads Scots DNA. She has no Chinese DNA
Son is born. The 50% he happens to receive from mom is Chinese. The 50% he happens to get from dad is Chinese. He has no Scots DNA.
Now irl this almost never happens so precisely, but you get the idea. Just because you have DNA from somewhere doesn't mean your child will inherit it, a parent has to be over 50% something themself, in order for every kid to inherit at least some of it genetically.
So instead, if Mom is 40% Scots and 60% Chinese, and dad is 75% Scots and 25% Chinese, both kids will each have at least SOME Scots and SOME Chinese showing up in DNA.
BECaUSE the least Chinese you can get from mom is 10% and the least Scots you can get from dad is 25%.

For example a person with a genotype of aabbcc would have the lightest skin tone since don’t have any uppercase letters in their genotype. But, for a person of AaBbCc would have a mixed skin tone since they have a mix of the two skin tones. So if a person with AAbbcc and a person with aaBbCc would have the same skin tone even thought their genotypes differ. A person who is parents are black(AABBCC) and white(aabbcc) would make a child who is in the mid tone skin colour(AbBbCc). But if the child(AaBbCc) has children with someone who has a genotype of a AaBbCc then the possible offspring could be 25% full white,50% mid, and 25% black. This illustrates that not everything is cut clean skin colour is a result of which genes you got from your parents one child could have gotten this gene while another could have gotten something completely different.
